{"ts":"2026-06-27T13:34:45.661Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Reviewing API Routes**\n\nI'm now diving into the Next.js API routes, the backbone of GFF AI's private dashboard and portal. I'm taking a close look at how these routes are structured and functioning, as they are crucial to the architecture. I'm investigating how data flows through them, specifically with respect to the `logs` feature.\n\n\n**Defining API Response Shapes**\n\nI'm now zeroing in on defining consistent response structures, starting with error responses. I want uniformity. I'm focusing on handling 401, 403, and validation errors. I'm also planning to implement simple pagination parameters. I am working to ensure that list endpoints do not leak sensitive information and that server-side RBAC checks are implemented.\n\n\n**Standardizing Error Responses**\n\nI'm now nailing down those consistent API response structures, really focusing on error handling. I've formalized the 404 response, along with the `400` and `500` error responses. I'm building out a plan to implement pagination on the user list endpoint. My goal is to ensure consistency and avoid information leakage, even in list endpoints. I've begun to add `limit` and `offset` query parameters.\n\n\n**Verifying Data Sanitization**\n\nI've just confirmed the `/api/v1/users` route successfully strips the `passwordHash` field from user entries, addressing the sensitive data issue in list endpoints. I've also verified that this is the only sensitive field, so this satisfies the requirement to avoid leaking sensitive information. Now I'm checking other routes that might return user information, starting with `/api/v1/auth/me/route.ts`.\n\n\n**Confirming Security Checks**\n\nI'm now verifying the RBAC boundary logic within each endpoint. I've confirmed password hashes are stripped in the `[id]` route too, as well as the `/api/v1/users` route. I'm actively inspecting the project list endpoint, and will inspect RBAC filters to see where boundaries are enforced server-side. I've begun to review `/api/v1/projects/route.ts`.\n\n\n**Refining Project Endpoint Security**\n\nI've just added pagination to the project list endpoint for consistency. I've also implemented robust filtering; non-admin users now *cannot* see projects from other clients. They receive a 403 error if a client ID filter doesn't match their own. I'm satisfied that this solidifies the RBAC model, so I will now refactor to improve code readability.\n\n\n**Validating Project Access**\n\nI'm now extending my security checks to the project detail endpoints. I'm focusing on the GET, PATCH, and DELETE methods within `app/api/v1/projects/[id]/route.ts`. I've confirmed GET returns a 403 for non-admin users if the client ID doesn't match. I'm actively verifying this consistent 403 error for PATCH and DELETE methods as well, to ensure that only admins can update or delete projects. My focus is on maintaining a consistent error shape across all routes.\n\n\n**Unifying Authentication Checks**\n\nI'm now zeroing in on standardizing how authentication is handled across the API. I'm reviewing the current `getAuthCaller` helper to see if it can be improved or unified. It's returning different error shapes in different scenarios, and I'd like to refactor it to return consistent error responses, and leverage it with a common middleware or standardized helper functions across the API routes. I'm focusing on ensuring every unauthenticated request consistently returns a 401 error with a standardized message. I am actively working on refactoring to get this consistent.\n\n\n"}}
